          'All Alone is an album by Frank Sinatra, released in 1962. All of the tracks on the album are torch songs, hence the lonely name of the album. Almost half of the tracks are written by Irving Berlin. The cover is a trimmed portion of painting that hung in Sinatraâs Palm Springs home.\n\nOriginally, All Alone was going to called "Come Waltz With Me." Although the title and the accompanying specially written title song were dropped before the albumâs release, the record remained a stately collection of waltzes, arranged and conducted by Gordon Jenkins.\nOut of all the arrangers Sinatra regularly worked with, Jenkins had the most overt classical influences in his writing, making him the perfect choice for the project. Nevertheless, All Alone is an uneven album, even as it is one of the most intriguing records Sinatra recorded.\nDivided between standards and relatively recent tunes, the most distinctive element of the album are the rich, neoclassical arrangements by Jenkins. Sinatra doesnât strictly follow Jenkinsâ intentions. Instead of playing close to the vest, he wrenches the emotions out of the songs. Most of the time, the results are quite moving, especially on the opening and closing Irving Berlin ballads, âAll Aloneâ and âThe Song Is Ended.â When the results arenât quite as successful, they are still interesting, and the elegant, rumanative music makes All Alone a necessary listen for dedicated Sinatra fans.\n\nTrack listing\n\n01 -- âAll Aloneâ (Irving Berlin) â 2:46\n02 -- âThe Girl Next Doorâ (Hugh Martin, Ralph Blane) â 3:21\n03 -- âAre You Lonesome Tonightâ (Roy Turk, Lou Handman) â 3:33\n04 -- âCharmaineâ, (Erno Rapee, Lew Pollack) â 3:22\n05 -- âWhatâll I Doâ (Berlin) â 3:18\n06 -- âWhen I Lost Youâ (Berlin) â 3:45\n07 -- âOh, How I Miss You Tonightâ (Benny Davis, Joe Burke, Mark Fisher) â 3:25\n08 -- âIndiscreetâ (Sammy Cahn, Jimmy Van Heusen) â 3:58\n09 -- âRememberâ (Berlin) â 3:28\n10 -- âTogetherâ (B.G. DeSylva, Lew Brown, Ray Henderson, Stephen Ballantine) â 3:23\n11 -- âThe Song is Endedâ (Berlin) â 3:29\n\nAlbum Notes\n\nReleased: October 1962\nRecorded: January 15âJanuary 17, 1962, Los Angeles\nGenre: Vocal Jazz\nLength: 37:48\nLabel: Reprise\n <a href="https://www.last.fm/music/Frank+Sinatra/All+Alone">Read more on Last.fm</a>. User-contributed text is available under the Creative Commons By-SA License; additional terms may apply.',
